properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River from Eildon to Seymour.

Minor flooding is likely along the Goulburn River downstream from Lake Eildon and at Seymour on Thursday morning.

  • No further flooding is expected along the Acheron River.
  • In the 24 hours to 11:00 pm Wednesday, rainfall totals up to 76 mm have been observed across the Goulburn River catchment. Further showers are forecast for the remainder of Wednesday and into Thursday.
  • The situation is being closely monitored and predictions will be revised as required.

Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour:
  • Minor flooding is likely along the Goulburn River from Lake Eildon to Seymour.
  • Minor flooding is possible at Trawool on Thursday morning.
  • The Goulburn River downstream of Lake Eildon is currently at 2.94 metres and steady, below the minor flood level. The Goulburn River downstream of Lake Eildon is likely to exceed the minor flood level (3.00 metres) on Thursday morning.
  • The Goulburn River at Seymour is currently at 3.56 metres and rising below the minor flood level. The Goulburn River at Seymour is likely to reach the minor flood level (3.80 metres) on Thursday morning.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one.
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock, pumps and machinery to higher ground.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
Eildon to Seymour: At Minor flood level 4.0 m on the Seymour Gauge:

  • Goulburn Caravan Park may start flood low lying parts of the park. The Caravan Parks at Molesworth and the Breakaway Caravan Park have been evacuated today.
  • Localised flooding along the river frontage between Kings Park and the old Hume Highway.
At Moderate flood level 5.2 m at Seymour:
  • Stormwater drains back flows into Emily Street.
  • Kings Park starts flooding.

Releases from Lake Eildon (for more information click or go to gmwater Managing Water Storages 2 pm 4/10/23)
  • GMW is closely monitoring Lake Eildon’s catchment conditions and rainfall to update storage inflow projections and make decisions about releasing water to manage the rate of fill.  The website advises that releases will be increasing in response to rainfall and increased inflows.
  • Releases will be gradually increased over the course of the afternoon (today) to 12,000 ML/d.
  • Releases will increase to 17,000 - 20,000 tomorrow (Thu 5/10/23).
  • This release is planned to keep the river level BELOW the Moderate flood level 5.2 m at the Seymour gauge.  
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 05/10/2023 12:10 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Wonnangatta River.

MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING ALONG WONNANGATTA RIVER AT WATERFORD

In the 24 hours to 1:00 am Thursday rainfall totals of up to 80 mm have been observed in the Mitchell River catchment, with one isolated total in the upper catchment around 101 mm. 

Further rainfall is forecast across the Mitchell River catchment during Thursday.

Wonnangatta River:
Major flooding is occurring along the Wonnangatta River at Waterford.
Waterford could be impacted anytime as Major flooding is currently occurring. If you are located in this area you are in danger - act now to protect yourself and move to higher ground. 
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
Stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 

Emergency services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay. 
Impacts in your area: 
  • Roads may be closed due to floodwater. For more information on road closures go to traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au. 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Some areas will be likely to lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 05/10/2023 11:30 am or as the situation changes.

This Major Flood Warning is being issued for the Ovens Rivers downstream of Rocky Point between Whorouly to Wangaratta.

Flood Warning Number: 6
NEAR MAJOR FLOODING POSSIBLE AT WANGARATTA FROM THURSDAY EVENING Minor flooding is continuing along the Ovens River at Bright, Eurobin and Rocky Point.
Since 9.00 am Wednesday, rainfall totals up to 35 mm has been recorded across the Ovens and King River catchments.
This situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point
Major flooding may occur along the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point.
The Ovens River at Wangaratta is currently at 11.24 metres and rising, below the minor flood level. The Ovens River at Wangaratta is expected to exceed the minor flood level (11.90 m) Thursday morning. The river level is likely to exceed the moderate flood level (12.40 m) Thursday afternoon and may reach the major flood level (12.70 m) Thursday evening.
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 

  • Rising floodwater can be dangerous. Be aware of water levels rising near you.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Decide and get ready to evacuate if it becomes necessary or you feel unsafe.
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation. 
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground IF STILL SAFE TO DO.
  • If in a flood risk area, be prepared to move household items to higher ground, on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
  • If you are camping close to the Ovens River, you need to move to higher ground, away from waterways. You may be at risk of flooding or your access road to safety cut by floodwater. 
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.     
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • At Major flood level in Wangaratta, flooding above floor level of some low lying homes and sheds are likely to occur in a few locations. 
  • Evacuation of a few houses may be required.
  • A small number of properties are likely to be impacted and possibly become isolated between in Doweling La
  • Many roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding, especially the Great Alpine Rd at Yellow Creek, travel via the Detour Road bypass. For more information on road closures, see below and go to traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.

A sandbag collection point will be open tomorrow morning (Thu) between 7 am and 1 pm on the corner of Handley St and Greta Rd (in the park next to the police station)  


At 11.9 m the Minor flood level in Wangaratta,
  • Water up to Yogi’s Chin in APEX Park .
  • Apex Park and farmland along the Ovens, King and possibly the Fifteen Mile Creek floodplains north, south and east of Wangaratta begin flooding. 
  • Bike paths and walking tracks around and downstream of Apex Park and the Northern Beaches are closed. Many riverside carparks are closed 

At 12.4 m Moderate flood level:
  • Water up to Yogi’s Mouth in APEX Park. Extensive flooding through Apex Park. 
  • Residents in Wilson and Parfitt Rd levees are advised to prepare to evacuate (Unless levee damage happens before this). 
  • Shallow flooding to Pinkerton Cres and backyards along Templeton St and Baker St. 
  • Widespread, deep flooding outside of the Parfitt Rd levee. 

At 12.7 m Major level flood, 6 cm lower than the Dec 2010 flood.
  • Water up to Yogi's nose.
  • Extensive road closures, including: Wilson Rd (outside levee area), Peechelba Rd at Seven Bridges, River Rd, Markwood-Everton Rd, Milawa-Tarrawingee Rd, Markwood-Tarrawingee Rd, Billabong Dve, Oxley Flats Rd, Stamps Lane area.
  • Widespread flooding around the airport and along the Ovens River flats north of Wangaratta to Peechelba and Bundalong and into the Stamps Lane area north of Wangaratta.
